If you don't have the content type saved in the database, you can try to detect the image format based on the binary data by looking at the signature (magic number) of the byte array. This is an ad-hoc solution and might not work with other image formats or missing/incorrect signatures.

Here's how you can do it:

1. First, create the following function in the view file, which checks if the byte array starts with a particular byte sequence:

```csharp
@functions {
    private bool ByteArrayStartsWith(byte[] array, params byte[] values)
    {
        if (array.Length < values.Length)
        {
            return false;
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < values.Length; i++)
        {
            if (array[i] != values[i])
            {
                return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }
}
```

2. Next, create a function to determine the content type based on the byte array:

```csharp
@functions {
    private string DetermineImageContentType(byte[] imgData)
    {
